            <h1>
                                UIC DPI Seed Program            </h1>
          
          
                <h2 class="element-invisible">You are here</h2><div class="breadcrumb"><a href="/">Home</a> <span class="separator">></span> <a href="/funding" title="">Funding Opportunities</a> <span class="separator">></span> <a href="/funding/internal-seed-funding" title="">Internal Funding</a> <span class="separator">></span> <a href="/uicdpi" class="active">UIC DPI Seed Program</a></div>          
        
        
        
            
      </div>

      <div class="layout-content main-content">
      
<section class="block block-system">
  
  
  <div class="content">
    <div>
      <article class="page node full">

  
  
  <div class="content">
    <div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p><span class="alert"> DPI Cycle 2 proposals are now due no later than <strong>5:00 pm CST on Friday, January 18, 2019</strong>. The submission portal will close promptly at 5:00 pm.</span></p>
<p>UIC announces a new program to catalyze UIC-led activities in support of the University of Illinois System’s Discovery Partners Institute (DPI). The UIC DPI Seed Program advances the mission of the DPI by investing up to $10 million from UIC’s royalties’ revenue accumulated at the System level to be used as “seed funds” for projects that will support the development of DPI. The UIC DPI Seed Program is created to align new UIC activities with the DPI’s priorities and mission. For more information on the DPI, see  <a href="http://innovation.uillinois.edu/">http://innovation.uillinois.edu/</a> The Chancellor’s Office will be soliciting applications over several cycles targeting the broad areas of <em>big data and cybersecurity; drug discovery and healthcare delivery innovations; and automated vehicles and mobility. </em>Applications in <em>other areas</em> that still meet the review criteria below are also welcome. Projects may consist of research, education and engagement activities, including interdisciplinary collaborations, and should be 6 months to 2 years in duration.</p>
<ul><li>Applications for <em>Cycle 1</em> are due November 1, 2018, 5:00 pm, with a project start in February, 2019. Budgets for Cycle 1 should not exceed $100,000 during the project period.</li>
<li>Applications for <em>Cycle 2</em> are due January 18, 2019, 5:00 pm, with a project start in March, 2019. Budgets for Cycle 2 should not exceed $250,000 during the project period.</li>
</ul><p>Application budgets should reflect actual needs of the proposed project. Target areas are the same for both cycles; Cycle 1 deadline is to rapidly fund smaller projects of more limited scope, whereas Cycle 2 deadline accommodates larger projects that require more time to prepare. If awarded, Project Director(s)/Principal Investigator(s) will be required to submit progress reports every 6 months and a final report at the conclusion of the project period. Templates for submitting progress reports will be distributed to awardees. The Project Director(s)/Principal Investigator(s) may submit more than one application for any cycle, provided the objectives of each application are distinctly different. Applications may include multiple Project Directors/Principal Investigators, as long as the individuals have complementary and integrated expertise. The contact Project Director/Principal Investigator must be a UIC faculty member with at least 0.5 FTE appointment at UIC at the time of the application and for the duration of the project period. All funds requested should be expended on UIC activities (i.e., no subcontracts are allowed to other organizations). Unpaid consultants or external contributors are allowed.</p>
<p>The UIC DPI Seed Program intends to fund up to <em>10 awards per Cycle</em> (10 in Cycle 1, 10 in Cycle 2). However, the actual number of awards funded is contingent upon the submission of a sufficient number of meritorious applications. The Chancellor’s office, in collaboration with the Office of the Vice Chancellor for Research, will conduct a review of applications and awards to determine the processes used for future funding cycles.</p>
<div class="accordions">
<p><article class="accordion collapsed"><header class="accordion-header"><br /><div class="icon"></div>
<div class="desc">
<h1>Eligibility</h1>
</div>
<p></p></header><br /><div class="accordion-body">
<ul><li>The contact Project Director/Principal Investigator must be a UIC faculty member with at least a 0.5 FTE appointment at UIC at the time of the application and for the duration of the project period.</li>
<li>Applications may include multiple Project Directors/Principal Investigators, as long as the individuals have complementary and integrated expertise.</li>
<li>The intent of the program is to encourage new UIC activities aligned with DPI’s priorities and mission. Participation by non-UIC personnel should be limited, confined to the role of key personnel, and be well justified. All funds must be expended on UIC activities (i.e., no subcontracts are allowed to other organizations).</li>
<li>Unpaid consultants or external contributors are allowed.</li>
<li>Project Director(s)/Principal Investigator(s) may submit more than one application for any cycle, provided the objectives of each application are distinctly different.</li>
</ul></div>
<p></p></article></p>
<p><article class="accordion collapsed"><header class="accordion-header"><br /><div class="icon"></div>
<div class="desc">
<h1>Deadlines</h1>
</div>
<p></p></header><br /><div class="accordion-body">
<p><strong>The submission portal will close at 5:00 pm. Late submissions will not be accepted.</strong></p>
<table border="1" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="1" style="width:500px"><tbody><tr><td>Cycle 1 Application</td>
<td><strong>November 1, 2018, 5:00 pm CST</strong></td>
</tr><tr><td>Cycle 1 <a href="http://research.uic.edu/dpisubmission">Revised Submission</a></td>
<td><strong>November 30, 2018, 5:00 pm CST</strong></td>
</tr><tr><td>Cycle 1 Projected Start</td>
<td><strong>February, 2019</strong></td>
</tr><tr><td>Cycle 2 <a href="http://research.uic.edu/dpiloi">LOI</a></td>
<td><strong>November 16, 2018, 5:00 pm CST</strong></td>
</tr><tr><td>Cycle 2 <a href="http://research.uic.edu/dpisubmission">Application</a></td>
<td><strong>January 18, 2019, 5:00 pm CST</strong></td>
</tr><tr><td>Cycle 2 Projected Start</td>
<td><strong>March, 2019</strong></td>
</tr></tbody></table></div>
<p></p></article></p>
<p><article class="accordion collapsed"><header class="accordion-header"><br /><div class="icon"></div>
<div class="desc">
<h1>Use of Funds</h1>
</div>
<p></p></header><br /><div class="accordion-body">
<h3>Allowable expenses:</h3>
<ul><li>
<div>Salary support for faculty (up to 2 months, subject to NIH salary cap limitations of $189,600 annually)</div>
</li>
<li>
<div>Consumable supplies</div>
</li>
<li>
<div>Animal costs and care expenses</div>
</li>
<li>
<div>Costs related to the use of human subjects</div>
</li>
<li>
<div>Salary and fringe benefits for students, post docs, research assistants, or technicians (administrative salaries are not allowed)</div>
</li>
<li>
<div>Travel for the purpose of field research or a specific, goal-oriented collaboration that will yield tangible outcomes. Travel to attend or present at a meeting or symposia is also an allowable cost.</div>
</li>
<li>
<div>Equipment</div>
</li>
<li>
<div>Tuition remission</div>
</li>
</ul><h3>Expenses not allowed:</h3>
<ul><li>
<div>Travel to principal sabbatical leave destinations.</div>
</li>
<li>
<div>Book publication subventions for non-refereed or commercial press</div>
</li>
<li>
<div>Indirect costs</div>
</li>
</ul></div>
<p></p></article></p>
<p><article class="accordion collapsed"><header class="accordion-header"><br /><div class="icon"></div>
<div class="desc">
<h1>Application Content and Order</h1>
</div>
<p></p></header><br /><div class="accordion-body">
<h3><u>Cover Sheet</u></h3>
<ul><li>Project title</li>
<li>Project Director(s)/Principal Investigator(s). In case of Multiple Project Directors/Principal Investigators, list all individuals and indicate who will serve as the primary contact
<ul><li>Primary Contact Email Address:</li>
<li>Primary Contact Phone Number:</li>
<li>College/School:</li>
<li>Department(s):</li>
<li>Position/Title:</li>
<li>Full-time or part-time faculty:</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Names and contact information of all private, public or non-profit partners in the proposed activity</li>
<li>Primary aim of activity (Select one from the following list)
<ul><li>Research</li>
<li>Education</li>
<li>Services</li>
<li>Partnerships/collaborations/interdisciplinary</li>
</ul></li>
</ul><h3><u>Project Abstract</u></h3>
<p>Provide a summary description of the project's goals, location, audience, and relevance to DPI vision (up to 250 words).</p>
<h3><u>Project Description </u></h3>
<p>The project description must address each of the following criteria (up to 500 words each):</p>
<p>Applicants are required to respond to the seven prompts below while adhering to stated word limits for each section.  No other sections are allowed.</p>
<p>Preliminary data are not required, however up to a total of five tables or figures may be included in the text. These may be inserted in any section (up to five total for the entire proposal, figures and tables combined). These tables, figures and legends will not count against the word limit per section.</p>
<p><strong>Required headers:</strong></p>
<p>Intellectual Merit, Alignment with DPI priorities, Long-term impact, Meaningful engagement, Sustainability, Strength and organization of project team, Feasibility.</p>
<p>Do not include separate sections for a summary of the project description, experimental design, R&amp;D, etc.  Extraneous sections will be deleted before review.</p>
<ol><li>Intellectual merit of the proposed work.</li>
<li>Alignment of proposed project with DPI priorities. This includes potential for creating jobs and enhancing economic development in Chicago and Illinois. Examples of this could include the potential of the project to increase the labor pool (workforce development) in critical areas; to stimulate entrepreneurship and innovation; or commercialization of new technologies.</li>
<li>Potential for long-term impact on UIC’s research, education and/or healthcare activities. For example, to what extent will the project expand research capacity, add new programs or services, and improve accessibility or quality of UIC activities.</li>
<li>Potential for meaningful engagement of private, public, or non-profit partners in the proposed activity.</li>
<li>Sustainability of efforts beyond the project period funded by the UIC DPI Seed Program (e.g., potential for support through subsequent grants or other sources of revenue).  </li>
<li>The strength and organization of the project team.</li>
<li>The feasibility of the proposed project. For projects involving human subjects or animals, please indicate if approved IRB/IACUC plans are in place.</li>
</ol><p>Each section of the project description should be no more than 500 words. Stated word count limits must be adhered to or your proposal will be disqualified and not reviewed. Microsoft Word 2016 will be the standard used to count words. Microsoft word is readily available for PC or MAC to the campus community at no charge from ACCC. Download Office 365 <a href="https://accc.uic.edu/service/office-365">https://accc.uic.edu/service/office-365</a>. Proposals exceeding the word limit for any section will not be reviewed.</p>
<p>Lists of references cited will not be counted toward the word limit, however, in-line citations in the text will be included toward each section word count. Section headers are not included in the word count. Figures, figure legends, and tables will not be included in the section word counts. Footnotes are not allowed.</p>
<p>Word limits are per section, and are not cumulative. Using less than 500 words per section does not allow carry-over of unused words to another section.</p>
<h3><u>Project timeline</u></h3>
<p>Include the projected timeline, milestones, and schedule of deliverables (up to 500 words)</p>
<h3><u>Detailed budget</u></h3>
<p>Dollar Amount Requested and Budget Justification (up to 500 words).</p>
<p>Detailed budgets must be included using the fillable budget <a href="http://research.uic.edu/sponsored_programs/preparing-proposal/developing-budget/budget-templates">template</a> from ORS web.</p>
<h3><u>Biosketches</u></h3>
<ul><li>Include a biosketch for all Project Director(s)/Principal Investigator(s).</li>
<li>Up to 5 pages each</li>
<li>NIH, NSF, or other format is acceptable</li>
<li>Do NOT include marital status, social security number, citizenship status, or other personal information not relevant to your research on your biosketch</li>
</ul><p><strong><em>Signatures:</em></strong> In lieu of signatures, applicants must check a box on the initial application form certifying that her/his department head has approved the application. Upon receipt, the system will send a confirmation email to you and your department head. Your head should reply to the email to confirm approval and that the contact PI has a faculty appointment of at least 50%.</p>
<p><strong><em>Approvals</em></strong>: Other institutional approvals and certifications need not be in place at submission.  However, in order to prevent delays with research involving human subjects please check with the Office for the Protection of Research Subjects (OPRS) to ensure your training meets their requirements and is up to date.</p>
</div>
<p></p></article></p>
<p><article class="accordion collapsed"><header class="accordion-header"><br /><div class="icon"></div>
<div class="desc">
<h1>Specific Formatting Guidelines</h1>
</div>
<p></p></header><br /><div class="accordion-body">
<ul><li>Calibri font, 11 point, single spaced</li>
<li>Margins no smaller than 1 inch in each direction</li>
<li>Embedded graphics are permitted</li>
<li>Each section of the project description should be no more than 500 words, and the entire project description should not exceed 7 pages Stated word count limits must be adhered to or your proposal will be disqualified and not reviewed. Microsoft Word 2016 will be the standard used to count words. Microsoft word is readily available for PC or MAC to the campus community at no charge from ACCC. Download Office 365 <a href="https://accc.uic.edu/service/office-365">https://accc.uic.edu/service/office-365</a>. Proposals exceeding the word limit for any section will not be reviewed.</li>
<li>Lists of references cited will not be counted toward the word limit, however, in-line citations in the text will be included toward each section word count. Section headers are not included in the word count. Figures, figure legends, and tables will not be included in the section word counts. Footnotes are not allowed.</li>
<li>Word limits are per section, and are not cumulative. Using less than 500 words per section does not allow carry-over of unused words to another section.</li>
<li>Biosketches should be no longer than 5 pages each, NIH, NSF, or other format is acceptable</li>
</ul></div>
<p></p></article></p>
<p><article class="accordion collapsed"><header class="accordion-header"><br /><div class="icon"></div>
<div class="desc">
<h1>Additional Guidelines</h1>
</div>
<p></p></header><br /><div class="accordion-body">
<ul><li>Applications should be for projects that are entirely new or clearly represent a distinct new direction if there is a relationship to ongoing work.</li>
<li>Preliminary data are not required; rather, it is expected that these funds will be used to support development of preliminary data that can be used in future extramural grant applications.</li>
<li>Research involving animals can be supported with DPI seed grants. However, IACUC approval must be in place or pending at the time of application.  Should a DPI proposal result in an award, an approval letter from the UIC ACC verifying approval of the SOW presented in the application will be required prior to distribution of funds.</li>
<li>Research involving human subjects, either clinical trials or observational in nature, can be supported with DPI seed grants. However, IRB approval must be in place or pending at the time of application.  Should a DPI proposal result in an award, an approval letter from the UIC IRB verifying approval of the SOW presented in the application will be required prior to distribution of funds.</li>
<li>No funds may be used to support collaborators outside of UIC, including for start-up companies founded or headed by UIC investigators.</li>
<li>Stated word count limits must be adhered to or your proposal will be disqualified and not reviewed. MICROSOFT WORD 2016 will be the standard used to count words. Microsoft word is readily available for PC or MAC to the campus community at no charge from ACCC. Download Office 365 <a href="https://accc.uic.edu/service/office-365">https://accc.uic.edu/service/office-365</a>. Proposals exceeding the word limit for any section will not be reviewed.</li>
<li>Lists of references cited will not be counted toward the word limit, however, in-line citations in the text will be included toward each section word count. Section headers are not included in the word count. Figures and figure legends will not be included in the section word counts. Preliminary data are not required, however up to a total of five tables and/or figures containing preliminary data may be included in the text. These may be inserted in any section (up to five total for the entire proposal, figures and tables combined). These tables, figures and legends will not count against the word limit per section. Footnotes are not allowed.</li>
<li>Word limits are per section, and are not cumulative. Using less than 500 words per section does not allow carry-over of unused words to another section.</li>
<li>It is expected funding awarded will be used within the proposed project period.  Requests for carryover of funds (No-Cost Extensions) at the end of the project period will be reviewed on a case by case basis and are not automatically guaranteed.</li>
</ul></div>
<p></p></article></p>
<p><article class="accordion collapsed"><header class="accordion-header"><br /><div class="icon"></div>
<div class="desc">
<h1>Application Checklist</h1>
</div>
<p></p></header><br /><div class="accordion-body">
<ul><li>Cover sheet</li>
<li>Project abstract</li>
<li>Project description</li>
<li>Project timeline</li>
<li>Budget requested and budget justification</li>
<li>Biosketch for each investigator</li>
</ul></div>
<p></p></article></p>
<p><article class="accordion collapsed"><header class="accordion-header"><br /><div class="icon"></div>
<div class="desc">
<h1>Submission</h1>
</div>
<p></p></header><br /><div class="accordion-body">
<ul><li>
<p>All components of the application must be combined into a single PDF file. If you are unable to combine the files, you will need Adobe Acrobat Professional software*. The system will not accept applications after the deadline.</p>
<p>You will receive a submission confirmation email which includes your cover page information.  Your department head will receive a notification that you have submitted the proposal and have attested that they have approved it.</p>
<p>	*Adobe Acrobat Professional Software is free for University of Illinois employees only.  </p></li>
</ul><p>Submission page: <a href="http://research.uic.edu/dpisubmission">http://research.uic.edu/dpisubmission</a> </p></div>
<p></p></article></p>
<p><article class="accordion collapsed"><header class="accordion-header"><br /><div class="icon"></div>
<div class="desc">
<h1>Post Award Obligations</h1>
</div>
<p></p></header><br /><div class="accordion-body">
<p>If awarded, Project Director(s)/Principal Investigator(s) will be required to submit progress reports every 6 months and a final report at the conclusion of the project period. Templates for submitting progress reports will be distributed to awardees.  These and other details will be outlined in the Notice of Award terms and conditions. </p></div>
<p></p></article></p>
<p><article class="accordion collapsed"><header class="accordion-header"><br /><div class="icon"></div>
<div class="desc">
<h1>FAQs</h1>
</div>
<p></p></header><br /><div class="accordion-body">
<table border="1" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="1" style="height:3028px; width:550px"><tbody><tr><td style="vertical-align:top">Q.</td>
<td><strong>Can we also team up with UIUC or Northwestern/UChicago/IIT? or are we restricted in the University partnership?</strong></td>
</tr><tr><td style="vertical-align:top">A.</td>
<td>
<div>Partnerships are encouraged, but the budget line items must be restricted to UIC only (no subcontracts are allowed).</div>
</td>
</tr><tr><td> </td>
<td> </td>
</tr><tr><td style="vertical-align:top">Q.</td>
<td><strong>Can we also team up with UIUC or Northwestern/UChicago/IIT? or are we restricted in the University partnership?</strong></td>
</tr><tr><td style="vertical-align:top">A.</td>
<td>Partnerships are encouraged, but the budget line items must be restricted to UIC only (no subcontracts are allowed).</td>
</tr><tr><td> </td>
<td> </td>
</tr><tr><td style="vertical-align:top">Q.</td>
<td><strong>If we want to partner with industry, does it need to be located in the State of Illinois?</strong></td>
</tr><tr><td>A.</td>
<td>No, an industry partner does not have to be located in Illinois.</td>
</tr><tr><td> </td>
<td> </td>
</tr><tr><td style="vertical-align:top">Q.</td>
<td><strong>Is there a restriction on the allocated budget? Can we use it toward student lines, supplies/services, etc.?</strong></td>
</tr><tr><td style="vertical-align:top">A.</td>
<td>Allowable expenses are outlined in the guidelines, but all expenses need to be justified to be in line with the project scope and objectives.</td>
</tr><tr><td> </td>
<td> </td>
</tr><tr><td style="vertical-align:top">Q.</td>
<td><strong>I would like to eventually create a NSF-funded Industry University Collaborative Research Center? Would a proposal to start this effort be a suitable one for this program?</strong></td>
</tr><tr><td>A.</td>
<td>Most certainly, as I/UCRC’s are directly aligned with DPI’s mission.</td>
</tr><tr><td> </td>
<td> </td>
</tr><tr><td>Q.</td>
<td><strong>Would the creation of a class at UIC be a fundable project under this program?</strong></td>
</tr><tr><td style="vertical-align:top">A.</td>
<td>Certainly, the seed funding program is to encourage a broad range of ideas. In this specific case, a course that is aligned with the mission of the DPI would be an appropriate proposal.</td>
</tr><tr><td> </td>
<td> </td>
</tr><tr><td style="vertical-align:top">Q.</td>
<td><strong>Do all the projects need to have activities that have a broad enough scope justifying $100K?</strong></td>
</tr><tr><td style="vertical-align:top">A.</td>
<td>Not all projects need to be proposed at $100K. For instance, the course project in the question above could mainly have a PI’s course release time as budget (typically 10-20k).</td>
</tr><tr><td> </td>
<td> </td>
</tr><tr><td>Q.</td>
<td><strong>What kind of commitment / support would be welcome from an industry partner?</strong></td>
</tr><tr><td style="vertical-align:top">A.</td>
<td>Matching funds support indicates a strong commitment to the proposed effort and would be considered a strong commitment.</td>
</tr><tr><td> </td>
<td> </td>
</tr><tr><td>Q.</td>
<td><strong>Do I need support letters from an industry partner in order to submit a proposal?</strong></td>
</tr><tr><td style="vertical-align:top">A.</td>
<td>While support letters are desirable and can make a strong proposal, they are by no means required.</td>
</tr><tr><td> </td>
<td> </td>
</tr><tr><td>Q.</td>
<td><strong>Are the project periods different for Cycles 1 and 2?</strong></td>
</tr><tr><td>A.</td>
<td>No. Both cycles allow a project period of 6 months to 2 years.</td>
</tr><tr><td> </td>
<td> </td>
</tr><tr><td>Q.</td>
<td><strong>Does the 7-page limit include references?</strong></td>
</tr><tr><td>A.</td>
<td>No. References may start on a new page and do not count toward the page limit.</td>
</tr><tr><td> </td>
<td> </td>
</tr><tr><td>Q.</td>
<td><strong>Is travel to academic conferences an allowable expense?</strong></td>
</tr><tr><td style="vertical-align:top">A.</td>
<td>"Travel to meetings or symposia" is not an allowable expense and would include academic conferences. However, travel for the purpose of "a specific, goal-oriented collaboration that will yield tangible outcomes" is allowed. IF the latter were planned to occur at a conference, it could be justified.</td>
</tr><tr><td> </td>
<td> </td>
</tr><tr><td>Q.</td>
<td><strong>Is the salary limitation per person or for the total budget?</strong></td>
</tr><tr><td style="vertical-align:top">A.</td>
<td>It is per person, i.e., each investigator can budget up to 2 months of salary up to the NIH cap of $189,600.</td>
</tr><tr><td> </td>
<td> </td>
</tr><tr><td style="vertical-align:top">Q.</td>
<td><strong>Is a professor emeritus employed part-time (less than 50%) who still conducts research and advises graduate students eligible to be a PI?</strong></td>
</tr><tr><td>A.</td>
<td>No.</td>
</tr><tr><td> </td>
<td> </td>
</tr><tr><td>Q.</td>
<td><strong>Will reviewers be internal to UIC or external?</strong></td>
</tr><tr><td>A.</td>
<td>All reviews will be conducted by UIC faculty.</td>
</tr><tr><td> </td>
<td> </td>
</tr><tr><td>Q.</td>
<td><strong>If a proposal includes proprietary data, will it be held confidential during review?</strong></td>
</tr><tr><td style="vertical-align:top">A.</td>
<td>Please indicate in your proposal if you have proprietary data covered by the terms of a university contract. As with any review, reviewers will be expected to not share privileged information. Reviewers will be notified that some proposals may contain propriety data considered confidential under UIC contracts.</td>
</tr><tr><td> </td>
<td> </td>
</tr><tr><td>Q.</td>
<td><strong>What are the criteria for reviewing proposals?</strong></td>
</tr><tr><td style="vertical-align:top">A.</td>
<td>
<p>The primary review criteria include the following:</p>
<ul><li>Academic merit of the proposed work.</li>
<li>Alignment of proposed project with DPI priorities. This includes potential for creating jobs and enhancing economic development in Chicago and Illinois.  Examples of this could include the potential of the project to increase the labor pool (workforce development) in critical areas, and to stimulate entrepreneurship and innovation as well as commercialization of new technologies.</li>
<li>Potential for long-term impact on UIC’s research, education and/or healthcare activities.  For example, to what extent does the project expand research capacity, add new programs or services, and improve accessibility or quality of UIC activities.</li>
<li>Potential for meaningful engagement of private, public, or non-profit partners in the proposed activity.</li>
<li>Sustainability of efforts beyond the project period funded by the UIC DPI Seed Program (e.g., potential for support through subsequent grants or other sources of revenue).  </li>
<li>The review committee will also take into account the following secondary criteria:
<ul><li>The strength and organization of the <em>project team</em></li>
<li>The <em>feasibility</em> of the proposed project including:  1) Is the projected timeline feasible and well-justified? 2) Are potential challenges and corresponding solutions discussed?</li>
</ul></li>
</ul></td>
</tr><tr><td> </td>
<td> </td>
</tr><tr><td>Q.</td>
<td><strong>Can additional sections be included for preliminary data or experimental plans?</strong></td>
</tr><tr><td style="vertical-align:top">A.</td>
<td>No. Preliminary data and experimental plans may be included, but they should be incorporated into the other sections as you deem most logically appropriate.</td>
</tr><tr><td> </td>
<td> </td>
</tr><tr><td style="vertical-align:top">Q.</td>
<td><strong>In the FAQ you mention fringe can be included. Is the money held in a state account? I thought fringe was not charged to state money, or is this not state money?</strong></td>
</tr><tr><td>A.</td>
<td>This money comes from royalites, not state appropriated funds.</td>
</tr><tr><td> </td>
<td> </td>
</tr><tr><td style="vertical-align:top">Q.</td>
<td><strong>As an Adjunct If I were to participate in an approved UIC project, am I eligible for up to 2 months of salary &amp; fringe benefits as a paid research assistant or technician?</strong></td>
</tr><tr><td style="vertical-align:top">A.</td>
<td>If you are a paid adjunct at UIC now and maintain a UIC position throughout the project term, you would be eligible to receive salary support for up to two months should the proposal you are part of be selected for funding.</td>
</tr><tr><td> </td>
<td> </td>
</tr><tr><td>Q.</td>
<td><strong>Is there a preferred format for the budget?</strong></td>
</tr><tr><td style="vertical-align:top">A.</td>
<td>There is no specific template required. You can use the ORS budget template form to help you decide what costs to include and generate a budget page. You will need to edit the template form as needed. The template can be found at this link: <u><a href="http://research.uic.edu/sponsored_programs/preparing-proposal/developing-budget/budget-templates" target="_blank">http://research.uic.edu/sponsored_programs/preparing-proposal/developing-budget/budget-templates</a></u></td>
</tr><tr><td> </td>
<td> </td>
</tr><tr><td style="vertical-align:top">Q.</td>
<td><strong>Are clinicians that are part of the Mile Square Health System eligible to apply for this program?</strong></td>
</tr><tr><td style="vertical-align:top">A.</td>
<td>As long as you fulfill the appointment eligibility (UIC Faculty member with at least a 0.5 FTE appointment at the time of application and for the duration of the project period), and plan to expend the funding on UIC activities, you would be eligible. Non-faculty clinical appointments and academic professional appointments are ineligible to be the contact PI.</td>
</tr><tr><td> </td>
<td> </td>
</tr><tr><td>Q.</td>
<td><strong>How do I calculate my salary request if my salary is above the NIH cap?</strong></td>
</tr><tr><td style="text-align:left; vertical-align:top">A.</td>
<td>You should make your salary calculation based on the NIH cap and indicate in the justification that the UIC salary is above the cap. You can adjust the effort as you see fit, but the total salary request per person should not exceed $42,133 ($189,600/ 9months *2 months).</td>
</tr></tbody></table></div>
<p></p></article></p></div>
<p><strong>Questions concerning the program may be addressed to RDS@uic.edu.</strong></p>
<p> </p>
</div></div></div>  </div>

  
</article>
    </div>
  </div>
  
</section>
      </div>
  
      
